{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.12,0,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9982"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55193"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6094"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23392"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a fall from a bicycle. He reports difficulty moving his right arm. Neurological examination reveals a loss of abduction of the right arm at the shoulder joint. There is also a small area of sensory loss over the lateral aspect of the shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Musculocutaneous","Radial","Median","Ulnar"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation suggests an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. This nerve innervates the deltoid muscle, which is responsible for abduction of the arm at the shoulder. Additionally, the axillary nerve provides sensory innervation to the skin over the lateral aspect of the shoulder, explaining the sensory loss in this area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm, affecting flexion at the elbow, not abduction at the shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for extension of the wrist and fingers, and its injury typically results in wrist drop, not loss of arm abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the innervation of the forearm and hand, particularly affecting thumb opposition and finger flexion, not shoulder abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the intrinsic muscles of the hand and is responsible for fine motor control of the fingers, not shoulder abduction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The axillary nerve is responsible for innervating the deltoid muscle, which is crucial for arm abduction.","Injury to the axillary nerve can result in loss of arm abduction and sensory loss over the lateral shoulder.","The radial nerve primarily affects extension of the wrist and fingers, not arm abduction."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55193"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55193"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T15:49:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T15:49:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9982"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{